Q\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NR\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NH\n|-\n|colspan=\"30\" | '''Former non-ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker Shoot-Out|Shoot-Out]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[1990 Shoot-Out|2R]]\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"19\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|Tournament Not Held\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:78%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! colspan=\"6\"|Performance Table Legend\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|LQ\n| lost in the qualifying draw\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|#R\n| lost in the early rounds of the tournament<br />(WR = Wildcard round, RR = Round robin)\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|QF\n| lost in the quarter-finals\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:yellow;\"|SF\n| lost in the semi\u2013finals\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|F\n| lost in the final\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#00ff00;\"|'''W'''\n| won the tournament\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|DNQ\n| did not qualify for the tournament\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|A\n| did not participate in the tournament\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|WD\n| withdrew from the tournament\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|DQ\n| disqualified from the tournament\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NH / Not Held || event was not held.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NR / Non-Ranking Event || event is/was no longer a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|R / Ranking Event || event is/was a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|RV / Ranking & Variant Format Event || means an event is/was a ranking & variant format event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|MR / Minor-Ranking Event || means an event is/was a minor-ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|PA / Pro-am Event || means an event is/was a pro-am event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|VF / Variant Format Event || means an event is/was a variant format event.\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==Snooker administration==\nIn December 1998 Ferguson was elected alongside [[Steve Davis]] and [[Dennis Taylor]] to the WPBSA's seven-person board, at the time led by [[Rex Williams]]. This appointment coincided with a period of difficulty between old and new board members.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/241543.stm|title=Davis leads fight for change|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=23 December 1998|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref> An attempt by Ferguson, Davis and Taylor to remove Williams and [[Bob Close]] in August 1999 failed, and a counter-motion saw the three voted off the board, although this was later reversed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hendry-quick-off-the-mark-1118179.html|last=Everton|first=Clive|authorlink=Clive Everton|title=Snooker: Hendry quick off the mark|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=29 August 1999|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nFerguson became the organisation's chairman in December 2001, replacing Mark Wildman. Ferguson was at the time ranked #56 in the world. He was criticised for endorsing the board's decision to fire chief executive Jim McKenzie one week after becoming chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/snooker-troubled-ferguson-falters-on-and-off--the-table-620865.html|last=Rowland|first=James|title=Snooker: Troubled Ferguson falters on and off the table|publisher=The Independent|date=21 December 2001|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter several years away from the post, Ferguson was re-elected as chairman of the WPBSA following a board meeting in July 2010.<ref name=WSL /> He survived a vote of confidence in December 2010 by a margin of 31 votes to three.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/wpbsa-backed-at-agm_sto2567314/story.shtml|title=WPBSA receives vote of confidence|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|date=3 December 2010|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Other roles==\nIn May 2009 Ferguson was elected as [[mayor]] of the civil parish of [[Ollerton and Boughton]] having previously spent two years from late 2006 as a town councillor in [[Ollerton]].<ref name=Advertiser>{{cite web|url=http://www.newarkadvertiser.co.uk/articles/news/Cued-up-as-mayor|title=Cued up as mayor|work=Newark Advertiser|date=9 May 2009|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> He was replaced as mayor by Irene Miller in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newarkadvertiser.co.uk/articles/news/New-mayor-named|title=New mayor named|work=Newark Advertiser|date=23 May 2010|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nFerguson also owns the bicycle repair shop called Wheels \u2018n\u2019 Things.<ref name=Advertiser/> He was a non-executive director of the [[Sherwood Energy Village]], an ecologically sustainable village on the site of a former coal mine in Ollerton;<ref name=Advertiser /> while the site still exists, the organisation went into liquidation in 2010.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-11108281 Sherwood Energy Village firm in liquidation - BBC News]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferguson, Jason}}\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mansfield]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Snooker referees and officials]]\n[[Category:People from Ollerton]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Jason Ferguson\n|image         = \n|caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1969|05|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Mansfield]], [[Nottinghamshire]], [[England]]\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Professional  = 1990\u20132004\n| High ranking  = 28 {{smaller|([[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/1995]])}} \n| Prize money   = \u00a3273,485\n| High break    = '''137''': <br> {{smaller|1998 Benson & Hedges Championship}} \n| Century break = 18\n| Best finish   = ''Last 16'' {{smaller|(x10)}} \n| Other wins = \n}}\n\n'''Jason Elliott Ferguson''' (born 31 May 1969) is a former professional [[snooker]] player and current chairman of the [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]].<ref name=billiards>{{cite web|url=http://www.billiardssnookers.com/players-profile/jason-ferguson.html |title=Jason Ferguson |publisher=billiardssnooker.com |accessdate=25 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316201711/http://www.billiardssnookers.com/players-profile/jason-ferguson.html |archivedate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> He reached the [[World Snooker Championship]] on three occasions, and was for four seasons ranked in the world's top 32 players, reaching a peak position of #28. \n\nIn 1998 Ferguson was elected to the board of the WPBSA, and became chairman of the organisation in 2001. After retiring as a professional player and leaving his position on the WPBSA, he served as the mayor of [[Ollerton and Boughton]] between 2009 and 2010. In July 2010 Ferguson was re-elected as chairman of the WPBSA.\n\n==Playing career==\nFerguson turned professional in 1990. Two years later he qualified for the [[World Snooker Championships]], losing in the first round, and reached the last 16 of the [[UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]]. He reached the same stage of six more ranking events but never progressed beyond that stage.<ref name=billiards />\n\nFerguson again qualified for the World Championship in [[1996 World Snooker Championship|1996]], again losing in the first round.<ref name=billiards /> His final World Championship appearance came in [[1998 World Snooker Championship|1998]], when he lost 8\u201310 to eventual champion [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-1998.asp |title=World Championship 1998 |publisher=Global Snooker |accessdate=25 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310201452/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-1998.asp |archivedate=10 March 2011 }}</ref> He spent a total of four years ranked among the world's top 32 players,<ref name=WSL>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2205308,00.html |title=Jason Ferguson Appointed WPBSA Chairman |publisher=worldsnooker.com |date=2 November 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612034813/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2205308%2C00.html |archivedate=12 June 2012 }}</ref> reaching his highest ranking of #28 in the 1994/95 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Rankings 1994/95|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/rk_9495.shtml|publisher=WWW  Snooker|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Ferguson continued to play professionally for a further six years, his form suffered due to his increased workload after being elected to the WPBSA board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/talkwales/chat/010423-010508/snooker/020430.shtml|title=Willie Thorne, John Williams, Jason Ferguson and Mark Johnstone Allen's Snooker Chat|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|date=30 April 2002|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref> He retired in 2004.<ref name=billiards />\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0 0; border:1px #aaa soli