" colspan=\"4\"|MR / Minor-Ranking Event || means an event is/was a minor-ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|PA / Pro-am Event || means an event is/was a pro-am event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|VF / Variant Format Event || means an event is/was a variant format event.\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==Snooker administration==\nIn December 1998 Ferguson was elected alongside [[Steve Davis]] and [[Dennis Taylor]] to the WPBSA's seven-person board, at the time led by [[Rex Williams]]. This appointment coincided with a period of difficulty between old and new board members.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/241543.stm|title=Davis leads fight for change|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=23 December 1998|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref> An attempt by Ferguson, Davis and Taylor to remove Williams and [[Bob Close]] in August 1999 failed, and a counter-motion saw the three voted off the board, although this was later reversed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hendry-quick-off-the-mark-1118179.html|last=Everton|first=Clive|authorlink=Clive Everton|title=Snooker: Hendry quick off the mark|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=29 August 1999|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nFerguson became the organisation's chairman in December 2001, replacing Mark Wildman. Ferguson was at the time ranked #56 in the world. He was criticised for endorsing the board's decision to fire chief executive Jim McKenzie one week after becoming chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/snooker-troubled-ferguson-falters-on-and-off--the-table-620865.html|last=Rowland|first=James|title=Snooker: Troubled Ferguson falters on and off the table|publisher=The Independent|date=21 December 2001|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter several years away from the post, Ferguson was re-elected as chairman of the WPBSA following a board meeting in July 2010.<ref name=WSL /> He survived a vote of confidence in December 2010 by a margin of 31 votes to three.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/wpbsa-backed-at-agm_sto2567314/story.shtml|title=WPBSA receives vote of confidence|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|date=3 December 2010|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Other roles==\nIn May 2009 Ferguson was elected as [[mayor]] of the civil parish of [[Ollerton and Boughton]] having previously spent two years from late 2006 as a town councillor in [[Ollerton]].<ref name=Advertiser>{{cite web|url=http://www.newarkadvertiser.co.uk/articles/news/Cued-up-as-mayor|title=Cued up as mayor|work=Newark Advertiser|date=9 May 2009|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> He was replaced as mayor by Irene Miller in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newarkadvertiser.co.uk/articles/news/New-mayor-named|title=New mayor named|work=Newark Advertiser|date=23 May 2010|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> \n\nFerguson also owns the bicycle repair shop called Wheels \u2018n\u2019 Things.<ref name=Advertiser/> He was a non-executive director of the [[Sherwood Energy Village]], an ecologically sustainable village on the site of a former coal mine in Ollerton;<ref name=Advertiser /> while the site still exists, the organisation went into liquidation in 2010.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-11108281 Sherwood Energy Village firm in liquidation - BBC News]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferguson, Jason}}\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mansfield]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Snooker referees and officials]]\n[[Category:People from Ollerton]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup - fix season links usingWP:AWB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jason_Ferguson_(snooker_player)"}
